In pure JavaScript, there is no exact equivalent to jQuery's `$(document).ready()` function. However, you can achieve similar functionality using the `DOMContentLoaded` event.

Here's an example of how to use it:

```javascript
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
  // This code will run once the document content is loaded and all elements are available.
});
```

The `DOMContentLoaded` event is fired when the initial HTML document has been completely loaded and parsed, without waiting for stylesheets, images, and subframes to finish loading. This means that the code inside the event listener will run as soon as the DOM content is loaded, without waiting for all external resources to load.

To show content only when the page is fully loaded, you can use the `window.onload` event in JavaScript. This event fires only when the entire page including its content, stylesheets, images, and scripts have finished loading.

Here's how you can use it:

```javascript
window.onload = function() {
  // This code will run once the page is fully loaded.
};
```

Note that in this case, the code inside the `window.onload` event will only execute once the page and all of its resources have finished loading, so there will be a delay before the content is displayed. 

To improve the perceived loading time, you can use CSS or JavaScript techniques to show a loading indicator while the page is loading, and hide it once the `window.onload` event fires.

To show nothing while the page is loading and only display content once it is fully loaded, you can use CSS or JavaScript techniques to create a loading indicator which will then be hidden and the content will be displayed once the `window.onload` event is fired.

Here's an example of how you can achieve this using CSS and JavaScript:

CSS:

```css
/* Begin with the indicator hidden */ 
#loader {
  display: none;
}

/* Show the indicator while the page is loading */
body.loading #loader {
  display: block;
}
```

